  "prompt": "If a chemical rocket had starting mass equal to Earth and final mass one billion tons, what would be its final velocity?",
  "response": "To solve this, I'll use the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation:\n\n\u0394v = ve * ln(m0/mf)\n\nWhere:\n\u0394v = change in velocity\nve = exhaust velocity\nm0 = initial mass\nmf = final mass\n\nChallenges:\n1. Mass of Earth \u2248 5.97 \u00d7 10^24 kg\n2. Final mass = 1 billion tons = 10^12 kg\n\nI'll assume a typical high-performance rocket exhaust velocity of 4,500 m/s (e.g., hydrogen/oxygen)\n\nCalculation:\nln(m0/mf) = ln(5.97 \u00d7 10^24 / 10^12)\n           = ln(5.97 \u00d7 10^12)\n           \u2248 28.7\n\n\u0394v = 4,500 * 28.7\n    \u2248 129,150 m/s\n    \u2248 129 km/s\n\nThis is an absurdly high velocity, showing the theoretical nature of the calculation. Practically, such a rocket is impossible.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this solution?",
